column169: New Pathology Sample Shipping/Packaging Plan As of 04/07/2017  1. Ship samples in a cardboard box containing an inner Styrofoam insert cooler to keep fluids and formalin contained.  2. Double Ziploc bag each sample and double check that the Ziploc bags are closed, sealed and all excess air is let out.  3. Para film container lids half way down the container for extra lid reinforcement.  4. New pathology sample containers have been ordered and will be used as soon as received that have a better screw on lid that won’t crack from the change in pressure on a plane like the containers we were using.  5. A pig mat will be placed in the Styrofoam insert cooler to absorb any fluids that do leak so they will be contained in the Styrofoam insert.  6. All samples will be wrapped in an extra biohazard bag for an extra layer of protection.  7. All patient confidential requisitions will be secured in their own Ziploc bag attached to the double zip locked sample to keep the paperwork from becoming contaminated in any leaks.  8. Make sure all samples are securely packed and surrounded by packing material to keep movement to a minimum.  9. All lab staff has been re-educated on the new shipping protocol for packaging pathology samples as of 04/07/2017.

column168: April 6, 2017:  Yardmaster at CR Morrisville, PA Yard notified CR Risk Manager A. Richter that during a routine mechanical inspection of an outbound train, Mechanical Inspector(s) noted tank car GATX 54227, containing the residue of Styrene Monomer, Stabilized, with a slight drip from the bottom outlet operating handle stem packing area.    Further inspection by CR Richter and Hepaco (CR's emergency response contractor) noted slight dripping originating from the bottom outlet valve stem where it was attached to the valve operating handle.  Due to its location up inside the tank car jacket (tank car jacketed/insulated), further inspection and repair was prohibitive.      A bucket with chemical absorbant pads was rigged under the outlet valve stem.  Due to a further inspection of remaining contents inside the tank through the manway, and those contents estimated between 10-15 gallons, it was decided that the car will be cleaned and purged on Monday, April 10.  Car will then be billed to home shop for inspection/repair/replacement of the internal bottom outlet valve.
column169: During the venting of the car's internal pressure prior to ability to safely open the manway cover, it was gauged that there was 18 psi of pressure in the car, seemingly excessive for what's required to unload the car.

When the package was picked up from the postal comp to be placed in a cargo container the package started to leak yellow powder. The powder was determined to be dry chemical from one of two fire extinguishers inside the box. The exterior of the outer package did not give any indication of the contents of the package. The spilled dry chemical was cleaned up by Northern Air Cargo employees and properly disposed of.    Pictures are available upon request.

On April 13, 2017, XPO Logistics (NKX Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN3082, WF Shredder, 9, III (PRO#556131682) release. According to the caller, terminal were loading a trailer (4414527) when the valve of (1) 275 gallon poly tote hit the trailer causing it to break off and the release. Approximately 260 gallons of product has been released to the trailer floor, dock floor and concrete beneath. The caller indicated that the majority of the release is on the concrete below the trailer. Contractor indicated that approximately 235 gallons of product has been lost. Approximately 2 gallons of the release has impacted the trailer floor. Approximately 1 gallon of product has impacted the dock floor. The remaining 232 gallons has been released to the parking area. Contractor is utilizing absorbent materials to clean the release at this time. Contractor is transferring the remaining product from the damaged tote into a 55 gallon poly drum. Contractor indicated that the release has impacted an area of 110' in length and a 50' wide area that narrows down to a 35' wide area. Contractor is using absorbent materials in the trailer and dock to clean the release. Contractor indicated that the trailer and dock floor have been cleaned. Contractor is waiting for the sweeper unit to arrive on site to finish cleaning the parking area. Contractor advised they have utilized approx. 120 bags of granular absorbents to continue to remove the product from the parking area. Cleanup actions are progressing. Due to the release impacting the cracks in the asphalt and being tracked through the parking area, contractor has been advised to work in portland cement onto the impacted areas. Cleanup actions are progressing. Contractor advised all cleanup actions are complete. They generated 15-55 gallon drums of waste and labeled them accordingly. All generated waste was staged in OS&D to be managed by OS&D personnel.

column168: ON APRIL 4, 2017, AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 PM, UNIVAR DRIVER HAD COMPLETED HIS TRANSFER WHEN HE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF CLEARING THE LINES OF PRODUCT USING CUSTOMER AIR WHEN THE CUSTOMERS HIGH LEVEL ALARM TRIGGERED AN AUTOMATIC VALVE TO CLOSE WITHOUT A VISUAL OR AUDIBLE NOTIFICATION. THE CLOSED VALVE RESULTED IN PRESSURE BUILD UP IN THE PRODUCT HOSE THAT RELEASE RESIDUAL PRODUCT WHEN DISCONNECTED FROM THE PUMP. IT ESTIMATED THAT 3 TO 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT DRAINED FROM THE HOSE THAT LASTED FOR LESS THEN 5 MINUTES. CUSTOMER USED OIL DRY TO KEEP MATERIAL FROM SPREADING AND CALLED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO COMPLETE CLEAN UP.   PLEASE NOTE: NO PACKAGING OR EQUIPMENT OF UNIVAR FAILED AND THAT IS WHY SECTION 25 WAS NOT COMPLETED.
column169: CUSTOMER WILL INSTALL PRESSURE GAUGE TO VERIFY NO PRESSURE IN THE LINE BEFORE DISCONNECTING. CUSTOMER WILL INVESTIGATE AND INSTALL A VISUAL AND AUDIBLE ALARM TO THE HIGH LEVEL VALVE TO ALERT EMPLOYEES WHEN THE VALVE CLOSES UNEXPECTEDLY.  UNIVAR WILL OUTFIT PUMP CARTS WITH AIR REGULATOR AND PRESSURE GAUGE TO MONITOR IF PRESSURE IS PRESENT, IN ADDITION TO A RELIEF VALVE THAT CAN BE PHYSICALLY CHECKED FOR BACK PRESSURE PRIOR TO DISCONNECTING ANY EQUIPMENT.  THE UNIVAR STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE WILL BE UPDATED TO INCLUDE THE ADDITIONAL EQUIPMENT TO BE USED AS WELL THE STEPS TO FOLLOW TO CHECK FOR RESIDUAL PRESSURE PRIOR TO BREAKING ANY LINES.

column168: At 1555 ERTS received a call from Sheila Sigley of Landstar to report a spill. It was reported that at 1518 hours Truck #420156 / trailer # 698203 was involved in a single vehicle accident resulting in the truck and trailer on its side in a ditch on I-86 in Cuba NY resulting in the release of approximately 5-10 gallons of diesel fuel and 10-15 gallons of motor oil. Fire Department was on scene and the Allegany County Police / Fire Department contacted IRM Services to conduct the intial cargo off load from the trailer and is beginning to off load the trailer at this time per the request of county police (per Chris of IRM). No cargo was reported to have been released. It was reported that no storm drains or waterways were impacted by this release at this time. Due to the released amount of petroleum being more than 5 gallons, ERTS contacted NYDEC to report the spill and received report #1700109. ERTS coordinated with a network contractor, T&R Environmental, to perform cleanup of the released tractor fluids, per Sheila Sigley's request. T&R Environmental arrived on site, confirmed 2 lanes were closed down and ERTS proceeded to contact the NRC and received report #117-4857 frin Petty Officer Greer at 1940 hours.     On April 19th 2017 ERTS received an itemized list of all product damaged in the multiple vehicle accident and found that (5) 5 Gallon pails of a UN1263 Paint related material (General Purpose Solvent) was damaged as a result of the accident releasing approximately 25 gallons to the trailer floor of the Landstar Trailer.

column168: Driver made a wrong turn and ended up on a one lane road.  While attempting to navigate the one lane road the trailer tires slide off the pavement and the weight of the trailer pulled it off the road, down an embankment. The angle of the trailer caused the product to flood the dome lid area allowing the product to seep from the improperly secured dome lid. Driver called in and wrecker was dispatched to the scene and upon arrival it was determined another wrecker was needed to secure the scene and prevent a rollover.  Upon arrival a wrecker driver noticed the smell of the product which made us aware the trailer was leaking.  Efforts were made at the time to collect the material dripping from the trailer and an environmental company was contacted.  Washington County Public Safety arrived on scene and secured the area including evacuating the four homes in a 150 foot radius. Product was trans loaded into another trailer. The original equipment was secured and the evacuation order lifted in an 8 hour period.

column168: On 04/07/2017 a Federal Railroad Administration Hazardous Materials Inspector performing inspections in the Cumberland Terminal, Cumberland, MD discovered AGLX 1125, a residue tank car of Propane leaking from the vapor valve inside the protective housing. The Shipper of Record - Amerigas, the National Response Center, and the Maryland Department of Environment were notified. CHEMTREC Report 2017-04-07-00163. Specialized Professional Services Incorporated, a CSXT Emergency Response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and discovered the vapor line valve not fully closed and the secondary closure plug without proper thread sealant resulting in a release of product vapor. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to Mr. Joe Kennedy of Amerigas, phone 304-813-5229. Contractor personnel secured the valve, removed the closure plug, applied commercial thread sealant and reinstalled. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code: 396  NARRI 5(4+5+0) x (2+0) = 90

On April 2, 2017 at 14:00 hours, personnel in the CSXT Radnor yard reported an odor in the area of SUJX 281043, a loaded tank car of Sulfur, Molten.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Sulcom, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2017-0402-00016.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that 3 of the 8 manway cover swing bolts were less than tool tight.  Additionally, MEI found that a buildup of solidified sulfur on the manway nozzles sealing surface was preventing an even closure of the manway nozzle cover.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative Kelle Brown (281-907-9275).  Ms. Brown did note that while Sulcom, Inc. is the shipper of record for this load; the car is loaded and secured by a third party company- Canal Terminal Logistics, Channahon, IL.  Contractor personnel opened the manway, inspected the manway gasket, removed the solidified sulfur form the nozzles sealing surface, and properly secured all manway cover bolts. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.    NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60  Cause Code: 200

column168: On April 17, 2017 at 0847 hours, personnel at CSXT Stanley Yard discovered GATX 200015, a loaded UN 1075, Liquefied Petroleum Gases, Not Odorized tank car to have a hissing noise coming from the protective housing area. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, was dispatched to the scene.  Upon inspection it was determined the o-ring was not seated in place properly. The car was isolated and the Shipper, The Andersons Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 20170407-00216.  A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, was dispatched to the scene. column168: On April 19, 2017 Landstar (Ref#56168 and 7219659) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1263, SB Yel Mo C/C Low Voc, 3, II, cargo release. According to the caller, the driver of tractor (56168) trailer (761268) went to re-fuel and noticed product leaking from the trailer. ERTS spoke with the driver. The driver indicated that approximately 20 gallons of product has been released to the trailer and the ground beneath. It is unknown in the cause of the release at this time. Contractor indicated that the release seems to have dried onto the trailer and pallet. Contractor indicated that there appears to be a drum with a hole in the bottom of it. Contractor indicated that the seam weld at the base of the drum was poor resulting in the release. Contractor indicated that approximately 5 gallons has been lost. Contractor has offloaded the impacted pallet at this time. Contractor is using absorbent materials to clean the release. Contractor has over-packed the damaged drum at this time. Contractor is re-palatalizing the drums at this time. The contractor confirmed that approximately 5 gallons was released. The released product became tacky and was easily scraped off once granular absorbents were applied. 1-85 gallon metal drum was generated consisting of the damaged paint drum. 1-55 gallon metal drum was generated consisting of impacted absorbents, debris, poly and sweepings.

column168: No On April 10, 2017 at 14:41 hours, FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector Kevin Cash reported at the CSX Bridgeport, AL interchange that tank car NATX 300152, a loaded tank car of Acetone was leaking.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Altivia, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2017-0410-00130.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSX response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that product was leaking from the threaded connection between the vacuum relief valve (VRV)  and the tank car.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (Luke Carey 740-533-5211).  MEI was able to tighten the connection of the VRV to the car; however, this did not stop the release.  MEI then removed the VRV and installed a solid pipe plug which secured the release.  The car was set out of transportation pending repair/requalification disposition from the shipper and/or car owner.       NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80  Cause Code: 1035
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On April 21, 2017 at 02:25 hours personnel in the CSXT Wauhatchie Yard discovered GATX 7516, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, Spent, leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Occidental Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2017-0421-00018.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the fill hole cover securement bolts were less than tool tight.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative- Charles Little (931-535-4415).  After inspecting the fill port cover gasket to ensure it was not damaged, MEI secured the fill port cover bolts and the car was released for transportation.      NARRI: 5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100  Cause Code: 224

column168: A Clean Harbors (CHES) van trailer containing a shipment of hazardous waste from an onsite Raytheon (RTN) building was being transferred to another Raytheon facility dock onsite for weighing and consolidation. The trailer once fully loaded was destined to the intended waste disposal facility. The RTN forklift operator misjudged the clearance and punctured a drum in the van trailer with the forklift blade while carrying/loading a pallet of drums. The CHES driver was in no way involved with the loading or unloading process. Raytheon emergency response personnel was immediately summoned, donned personal protective equipment maneuvered the drum to stop the leak.  The contents of the punctured drum were transferred into an empty drum.  Absorbents were deployed onto the truck, and were collected and drummed. The area beneath the truck was inspected, and showed no indication of the released material. The shipment was then loaded without further incident. The initial estimates of the spill was approximately 2 to 5 gallons; but it was later estimated to be 1 to 2 gallons.  The Driver notified his supervisor of the spill who then notified the CHES's Transportation Compliance Specialist, Albert Giraldez. The spill was reported to the MA DEP on 4/6/17 at 13:18 to Ken Sanderson; the tracking number 3-34158 was assigned.  DEP subsequently contacted the Andover Fire Department; no emergency responders were deployed to the site.
column169: To prevent this incident from occurring again, Raytheon removed the powered industrial truck license from the fork lift operator, pending their full training.  Raytheon has also changed their loading procedures to include the use of a pallet jack rather than a forklift and a second person to serve as a spotter.  The incident was shared with leadership and our training vendors to increase awareness to other similar facilities.

column168: A CUSTOMER CALLED IN AND ORDERED 7500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL FOR THEIR   12,000 GALLON AST. WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED HE READ THE GAUGE AND ASKED THE QUESTION "WILL THE LOAD FIT" TO THE EMPLOYEE THAT REQUESTED THE DELIVERY. EYRE BUS SERVICES FILLED SOME OF THEIR BUSES TO MAKE ROOM FOR THE LOAD AND THEN INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVER THAT THE LOAD WOULD FIT.    THE DRIVER BEGAN TO FILL THE TANK, HE WAS WATCHING THE GAUGE AND STANDING AT THE CONTROLS. AT 88" THE TANK BEGAN TO RUN OVER, SPILL APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS ONTO THE CONCRETE AND BLACKTOP BELOW. THE TANK IS A 96" TANK AND AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION WE DETERMINED THAT THE GAUGE WAS OFF 8". THE OVERFILL PROTECTION (PNEUMERCATOR MODEL LC1000) ALSO FAILED TO OPERATE.    MDE NOTIFIED @ 1912 HOURS REPORTED TO ERIC OLAH.
column169: EYRE BUS SERVICE WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE GAUGE NEEDS TO BE RECALIBRATED AND THE OVERFILL PROTECTION MUST BE REPAIRED OR REPLACED.

column168: A driver had picked up a shipment of hazardous waste and was en-route to the intermediate truck transfer facility when he was flagged down by another motorist who advised him there was liquid coming out of his vehicle.  Both drivers pulled over and after opening the rear door discovered that a 330 gallon tote had cracked down the side, spilling most of it's contents.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and transferred the remaining 100 gallons into 2-55 gallon drums, along with the absorbent pads used to clean up the spilled liquid from the truck floor, ground, and other vehicle.  The truck then proceeded to the intermediate truck transfer facility for a thorough cleaning.  The drums were placed on the dock and after checking them for reaction and testing them, were loaded onto a vehicle destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: Both the Safety Kleen and the other vehicle were thoroughly washed of the spilled waste and returned to service.  The damaged tote was a little over a year old and is being returned to the manufacturer for testing.  No reason for the crack has been found at this time.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 4/4/17 at approximately 11:36 during deramp operations, product was observed leaking from the rear of the DRYU 243006 container and approximately one gallon of product leaked onto the ground trackside. The unit was immediately moved to the containment pit and United Pumping was dispatched for the required response.     Upon arrival, United Pumping observed the container leaking at the containment pit. Approximately one gallon leaked onto the containment pit floor. The interior inspection revealed cases of the Hazardous Material (Marine Pollutant) stacked in two rows and two layers in height; stretch wrapped and palletized. The container deck was saturated with leaking product and several of the cases are leaking. No methods of securement to prevent cargo movement was observed in this shipment. It appears the cargo has shifted and the weight stowed on top  is crushing the cases at the bottom layers.  United Pumping personnel responded trackside to clean the leaking product from the ground.  An empty 40' container was mobilized by the shipper for transfer operations.    During the remediation of the leaking unit by United Pumping, a total of (4) cartons were discovered leaking. Each carton contained (2) plastic bottles (2.5 gallons each) of BRANDT GH ZINC (Hazardous Material). All (8) bottles in the compromised cartons were empty; resulting in a total of (20) gallons of leaked product. The leaking cartons were found at both upper and lower layers; at the rear, midpoint and nose section of the container. Bottles at upper layers were compromised when adjacent pallets shifted and punctured the bottles. Bottle at lower layers were compromised due to excessive weight stowed directly on top.  United Pumping completed transfer of cargo into TGHU519314. Cargo was stowed only one layer in height and properly secured with Air Bags and Ty Gard applications, at midpoint and the rear. Both units were released for outgate. Waste materials were packaged and secured within the container for shipper handling.
column169: Proper blocking and bracing should be utilized by the shipper prior to placing a container in transportation.  A review should be conducted with loading personnel to ensure they understand the proper loading and securement procedures to avoid shipment/container damage during transportation.

Approximately 1 cup of UN3098 "AFCO 4365 Hyper Flex" released from a 300 gallon poly tote due to a loose cap. The release impacted the trailer floor. The leaking tote was accepted by the consignee and a contractor responded to neutralize and clean the impacted area on the trailer floor. All waste was containerized for proper disposal.

One 55 gallon metal drum containing UN1866 Resin Solution was crushed after being dragged on the trailer floor releasing approximately 8 liquid ounces of material to the trailer floor. Terminal personnel performed cleanup operations. The damaged drum along with the cleanup debris was placed into a salvage drum which was staged onsite pending disposition. No drains, soils, or waterways were impacted.

While off-loading a 1A2 drum at the Veolia 10-day intransit facility located in Blaine, MN, a small hole was observed on the side wall of the drum. Approximately 0.5 pint of liquid was released from the container. The container was not supposed to container free liquids. The spill was absorbed using oil dry and absorbent pads. The drum was placed into a poly salvage drum along with the spill debris.
column169: The incident was reviewed with the original shipper to ensure that no free liquids are shipped with this waste material. If free liquids are unavoidable, then a different suitable packaging is required.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0135, ON APRIL 26, 2017, RESPONDER WAS DISPATCHED TO SORT ISLE DOOR 16. RESPONDER WAS INFORMED OF A LEAKING HAZMAT LOCATED ON THE PRIMARY. THE PRIMARY BELT WAS OFF. RESPONDER ARRIVED AT THE AREA WITH THE SPILL CART AND WEARING ALL APPROPRIATE PPE. A 15' PERIMETER WAS ESTABLISHED. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE A FLAMMABLE LIQUID 3 THAT WAS LEAKING AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS ON THE BELT. USING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, PROPER CLEAN UP OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS DONE. THE LEAKING PACKAGE AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS CONTAINERIZED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DAMAGE CAGE FOR PROCESSING.
column169: IT APPEARS THERE MAY HAVE BEEN 2 THINGS THAT CONTRIBUTED TO THE SPILLAGE OF THIS PACKAGE. THE CLOSURES ON THE BOTTLES DID NOT APPEAR TO BE VERY STRONG. CAPS WERE NOT HEAVY DUTY AND APPEARED TO BE EASY TO DISLODGE. ALSO, WHEN UNLOADING, THE UNLOADER PLACED THE PACKAGE ON ITS SIDE TO ALLOW THE LABEL TO BE SCANNED. PLACING THE PACKAGE ON ITS SIDE MAY HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO DISLODGING THE CAPS. TO PREVENT THIS, IT WOULD BE ADVANTAGEOUS FOR THE SHIPPER TO ALWAYS PUT THE LABEL ON TOP OF THE BOX. ALSO, TO PREVENT PACKAGES FROM LEAKING,IT WOULD BE BEST FOR UNLOADERS TO PAY MORE ATTENTION TO ORIENTATION ARROWS, REGARDLESS OF WHERE THE LABEL IS.

column168: R&C RIVER’S FARM DRIVER, BRAIN JOHNSON, WAS TOWING A PORTABLE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TANK WITH HIS TRUCK TO THEIR FIELD. WHILE MAKING A RIGHT TURN FROM STATE ROUTE 207 TO CROWNOVER MILL ROAD (NEW HOLLAND, OHIO), THE COLLAR UNDER THE LEAF SPRING FAILED CAUSING THE TANK TO SHIFT AND SEPARATE FROM THE RUNNING GEAR (THAT IS THE TRAILER THE PORTABLE TANK SITS ON). THE TANK CAME TO REST ON THE PAVEMENT BUT HAD DAMAGED THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE CAUSING THE RELEASE OF LIQUID AND VAPOR ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. THE LIQUID WAS CONTAINED IN THE GROUND AT THE INTERSECTION AND THE VAPOR WAS RELEASED INTO THE AIR. THE VAPOR CLOUD WAS VISIBLE IN THE AIR AND EVENTUALLY EVAPORATED. THE GROUND THAT WAS SATURATED WITH LIQUID ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS EXCAVATED AND LAND APPLIED IN A FARM FIELD NEAR THE INCIDENT SCENE. THE NURSE TANK WAS UP-RIGHTED AND REMAINING PRODUCT IN TANK WAS TRANSPORTED TO CO-ALLIANCE, LLP FACILITY. APPROXIMATELY 750 GALLONS OF LIQUID ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANK. APPROXIMATE TIME BETWEEN ROLLOVER AND COMPLETION OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 8 HOURS.     NRC #: 1175730  EPA REPORT #: 1704-65-0763  PICK-A-FAY FIRE DEPARTMENT  PICK-AWAY COUNTY SHERIFF’S DEPARTMENT

column168: Carrier First Class Transport spotted trailer to load material supplied by shipper-Georgia Pacific. The carrier had cleaned the trailer and failed to close the internal valve. GP operations checked that the outer valve was open and cap off to check for internal  valve leakage during loading, however failed to check that the internal valve was in the closed position per standard operating procedure. Flow of material was started into the trailer, beginning the loading process. When the loader went back to the valve to check for leaks and secure, it was discovered that the internal valve was open and material was running from the trailer into containment. There was no equipment failure, release caused by carrier presented for loading with the internal valve in the open position, loader failed to recognize that the valve was not close prior to beginning the loading process. All material was contained with no external release, recovered and cleaned up by the shipper.
column169: Facility counseled employee per company policy. Communication sent to operations on incident, carrier notified and informed of the error of bringing trailer in with valve open. Incident reported in company incident reporting system, root cause investigation performed and documented

column168: SCMX 6436 was noted as emitting an odor from the tank car itself. BNSF responder ascended the car and opened the protective housing lid to find a "Scully" overfill protection sensor bubbling product from within. The release was less than a liquid pound overall and was contained to the protective housing with no product leaking outside of that housing.   Shell was advised of the situation and stated that there were a bad batch of these sensors on some of their cars, but they thought that they repaired them all.  Shell hired contractors to monitor the car until their repair crew from Canada arrived to repair the car. The repair was made and the car moved under an OTMA-3 to destination for offloading then to Home Shop for re-certification.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT, RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 3,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL TO THE ASPHALT ROADWAY. ATLANTA FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. UPON ARRIVAL, DIESEL FUEL WAS DETECTED ON THE ASPHALT ROADWAY, ADJACENT ROADSIDE SOILS, AND ENTERED INTO DRAINAGE SWALE ALONG INTERSTATE. CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. CLEAN HARBORS USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE AFFECTED ASPHALT, RECOVERED FREE LIQUID FROM THE DRAINAGE SWALE WITH THE USE OF A VACUUM TRUCK, AND SECURED SITE PENDING EXCAVATION OF IMPACTED SOILS. FREE LIQUID DID NOT MIGRATE OFF SITE OR THREATEN TO IMPACT STATE WATERS. UPON RECEIPT OF APPLICABLE PERMITS, CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL RETURNED TO EXCAVATE CONTAMINATED SOILS, AND RESTORED SITE TO PREEXISTING CONDITION. DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED PER LOCAL, STATE,AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE'NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

At 0920 ET on April 08, 2017, an XPO Logistics tractor (#5326475) trailer (#3175288) was involved in a single vehicle rolloff accident resulting from heavy rain and poor roadway conditions.  The incident resulted in 1 55-gallon poly drum of UN2491 "P1-104 Ph Adjuster" being crushed.  All 55 gallons of product were released to the inside of the trailer, the roadway, nearby soils, and eventually a nearby river.     At 1025 ET on April 082, 2017, XPO logistics retained Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) to oversee cleanup operations. ERTS dispatched H2O Environmental (H2O) to provide initial cleanup operations and to oversee all necessary corrective actions.    H2O arrived onsite at 1326 ET on April 08.  Their personnel immediately set up a containment perimeter with absorbent boom.  The heavily impacted soils were excavated on that date.  Additionally, 15000 gallons of water was vacuumed from the impacted river.  All impacted materials were overpacked and taken offsite for pending disposal.    H2O returned to the site on April 25 to complete corrective actions.  On that date, all remaining impacted soil (estimated 50 tons) were removed and taken offsite for pending disposal.  Following the activities, the location was restored to near-original conditions.
column169: Better driver training may have prevented the release.

column168: 4/27/2017 0600: 53 gallon spill of unleaded gasoline to concrete pavement due to Driver/Operator error. Details - Lion Oil Transportation Dispatcher received a call from Lion Oil driver stating that he had just spilled, in his estimation, approximately 50-70 gallons of gasoline while dropping (off-loading) product at the Circle K Convenience store in Terrell, TX. Dispatcher immediately called the on-call Lion Transportation Safety Manager. Upon arrival at the spill scene, The Safety Mngr. aided the Driver who had already begun to cordon off the area around the spill: the spill was all contained on concrete and was small in diameter - approximately 20 ft. X 50 ft. The cargo tank is supplied with several spill pads, which the driver had thrown down over the main spill area. The Driver reported the incident to CHEMTREC Rpt.# 2017-04-27-00048 at 6:45am, and the store manager called the local Fire Dept. who responded, saw that the spill was contained and left the scene. TAS Environmental responded at approximately 0900 and cleaned up the spill by 0930.  Apparently, the Driver had not taken a depth measurement (called "sticking") of the receiving tank at the Circle K store; there is also an electronic device (Veeder) inside the store that is used to monitor tank volume. The driver also failed to correspond the tank depth with the Veeder reading, and estimated the amount that the receiving tank could hold, which resulted in overfilling the receiving tank. Findings:  > Driver is a short time employee; Unloading procedures not followed.  > Driver was not concentrating on work due to family issues on his mind.   > Driver failed to call dispatch when he got the initial veeder reading indicating that 90 % ullage/outage had already been reached which was not enough room to receive the remainder of the cargo tank contents.  > Driver did not take a "stick"/depth reading of tank prior to unloading.  > Driver used compartment 4 to "top off" the store tank which would have been only a partial load; Drivers are to drop entire compartment or none at all .This is a violation of company procedures.
column169: > Driver was reprimanded for not following operational procedures and company policy.  > Driver will receive additional training and testing regarding loading and off-  loading procedures at retail outlets.  > Driver was reminded that his safety and the safety of others requires him to keep his mind on his work at all times while on the job.  > This incident was distributed and reviewed with all Lion Oil/Delek US Drivers at the last quarterly safety meeting.  > Lion Oil Transportation Safety Management will add this type of event to our Key Performance Indicators as a "lagging" metric to determine where improvements can be made to the process/procedures.

column168: Carrier was unloading CMTV at consignee.  Driver connected hose with male connector to the connection at Consignee which also had male connector.  Driver used an adapter between the 2 male connectors.  Driver turned on pump and started unloading, then he noticed product leaking from the adapter.  Driver turned off the pump to stop the flow of product.    The adapter was not fully tightened when driver connected to hose.  Driver cleaned and reconnected the hose to the adapter making sure it was completely connected and tightened.    Duration of the release was about 30 seconds.  Consignee employee and driver cleaned up the spill material by washing into drainage within the contained area at Consignee.   Event 64176

column168: April 20, 2017:  At approximately 2245 hours, Conrail Car Inspector, performing an inbound inspection of CSXT train Q433-20, noted product leakage originating from the top of tank car PPRX 55015, load, Heptanes.    Further inspection by CR and emergency response contractor Hepaco noted leak origin at liquid valve closure flange due to six (6) loose securement nuts, allowing the interior ball valve to "float" causing a lack of securement.    Bolts secured and car watched for several hours with no further incident.  Car okayed to move to original destination for normal unloading. (NAR: 284)

column168: During a routine DOT Inspection of a Clean Harbors tanker, the DOT Inspector observed a small leakage coming from an external valve.  The inspector notified the driver of the leaking valve and the driver attempted to push the external valve closed, but had no effect on the leak.  It was determined the internal valve was opened and when the driver closed the internal valve through an emergency Shutoff valve the leak stopped.  The driver cleaned up the small amount of material and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: Strongly reminded the driver that all valves must be properly closed prior to moving a tanker for transit.

column168: After braking for traffic at a toll plaza, our driver noticed the hazmat spraying from the top of the trailer onto the side of the CTMV. Our driver pulled off to the shoulder of highway and stopped.  The front washout cover was missing.  The release lasted about 10 minutes, as some hazmat continued to release until the lading stopped sloshing.  A replacement washout cover was installed.  Subsequent CTMV inspection shows no damage to the washout port.  Since the missing cover was not recovered, we are not able to verify if it was damaged.    Our reference no: QC E64376

CN Mechanical Department employee observed liquid coming from the bottom outlet on car DBUX 301543 ( Residue, Alcohols N.O.S.- UN 1987) during an inspection at Waterloo Yard; Waterloo, IA. All appropriate departments notified, with tank car isolated.     CN Response Team responded noting seals in-tact. Bottom outlet valve was found to have a defective teflon gasket, allowing product to escape from the car. Bottom outlet cap was secured and car set out for OTMA-3 from shipper for home shop repair.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0235 ON APRIL 27, 2017, RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO PD-9/10, DOOR 58 FOR A REPORTED LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGE. RESPONDER ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION WITH THE SPILL CART AND WEARING ALL APPROPRIATE PPE. A 15' PERIMETER WAS ESTABLISHED. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE A FLAMMABLE LIQUID 3 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGE. THERE WAS A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON THE FLOOR. USING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE AREA WAS CLEANED. THE PACKAGE AND ALL SPILL RELATED MATERIALS WERE CONTAINERIZED AND BROUGHT TO THE DAMAGE CAGE FOR PROCESSING.
column169: THIS PACKAGE WAS POORLY PREPARED FOR TRANSPORT. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS IN METAL CANS. ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT OF KRAFT PAPER WAS USED FOR PACKING. IT WAS ONLY USED ON TOP OF THE CANS. NO PACKING MATERIAL WAS IN BETWEEN THE CANS. CANS WERE PACKED IN A SINGLE WALL BOX. DURING THE SORTING PROCESS AND DURING TRANSPORT, THE CANS WERE CONTINUALLY COMING INTO CONTACT WITH EACH OTHER. ALL CANS WERE DENTED IN MANY AREAS, AND ONE CAN WAS EVENTUALLY GOUGED AND BEGAN TO LEAK. BETTER PACKING PROCEDURES MUST BE USED TO TRANSPORT SUCH FRAGILE CONTAINERS. PACKAGE WAS ALSO PRINTED WITH THE FOLLOWING: "USED FOR 4-1 GAL. PLASTIC JUG" THE CONTAINERS INSIDE WERE METAL.

column168: THE IRREGULAR SORTER NEAR DOOR 201 WENT TO MOVE A HAZMAT PACKAGE   IT BEGAN TO LEAK ALL OVER THE ROLLERS. HE NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR   THE SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. I CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY, I USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT SO SOLIDIFY THE LIQUID ON THE ROLLERS   THE FLOOR UNDERNEATH. I SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS   PUT IT INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY. I TOOK THE PACKAGE   2 MORE THAT HAD GOTTEN LEAKED ON TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT THE GLASS BOTTLE INSIDE HAD CRACKED/SHATTERED.

column168: NOTE - The exact nature of the failure provided is what was concluded to be the most likely cause of the incident based on investigation.  The outlet valves for this cargo tank motor vehicle were removed and sent out for testing and found to have no defect, and we were unable to verify if any foreign object(s) prevented the valves from closing completely.    We have concluded that during loading of the material into the CTMV, a human error allowed some of the material to fill the space between in the internal and external outlet valves.  This material was initially intended for delivery to a different destination, but was not accepted, and routed to an alternate destination after being held in transportation for several days.       During the trip to deliver the material to the new destination, the vehicle was stopped for inspection by the Ohio State Highway Patrol.  During inspection it was noted that material began leaking from the outlet cap.  The driver assisted in spill response procedures and also vented the dome lid on the CTMV noting that a substantial amount of pressure was released through the dome lid once it was opened.  Once pressure was released, the leak from the valve appeared to stop.  Maintenance personnel dispatched to evaluate the issue and take initial corrective action determined that replacing the gasket in the outlet cap was sufficient to ensure no release of the material would occur.    The vehicle returned to operation and delivered the material to its destination roughly an additional 20 miles without further release.    Roughly 0.5 gallons of material was collected in the cleanup effort over the course of the 4 hours that elapsed between the commencement of the inspection at 08:05 and 12:00 when transportation continued to the destination.    It was determined that the most likely cause of the leak from the external valve was gasoline vapor pressure buildup between the internal and external valve, as material was trapped between the two valves.  The gasket on the outlet cap also failed to hold the material leaking from the external valve.
column169: The terminal that manages this transportation is re-training drivers on the importance of the proper management of valves on their vehicles during loading and unloading operations.  Additionally, drivers will be trained to inspect the valve outlet prior to loading to ensure no foreign object(s) are present that could affect a valve's ability to close properly.

AS THE HILL BROTHERS, (HB) TRUCK ARRIVED AT THIS LOCATION A U OF A EMPLOYEE UNLOCKED THE GATE SO THE HB DRIVER COULD BACK THE VEHICLE UP TO THE RECEIVING STORAGE TANK. THE HB DRIVER SECURED THE VEHICLE AND PROCEEDED TO CONNECT THE TRAILERS HYDROCHLORIC ACID, (HCL) PRODUCT TRANSFER HOSE TO THE RECEIVING SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE, (BLEACH) STORAGE TANK FILL CONNECTION WHICH IS LOCATED ADJACENT TO THE RECEIVING STORAGE TANK. THE DRIVER SECURELY FASTENED THE TRAILER PRODUCT HOSE CONNECTION TO THE RECEIVING STORAGE TANK FILL CONNECTION, OPENED THE RECEIVING STORAGE TANK FILL CONNECTION VALVE THAN WALKED BACK TO THE TRAILER TO START THE FILLING PROCESS. SHORTLY AFTER THE VALVES WERE OPEN ON THE TRAILER THE DRIVER NOTICED THE ORDER OF CHLORINE ALMOST IMMEDIATELY.     THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT BY TURNING THE VALVE ON THE TRAILER TO THE CLOSED POSITION.    THERE WAS A TIME LAPSE OF APPROXIMATELY 1 MINUTE 9 SECONDS FROM THE POINT THE TRAILER VALVE WAS OPENED TO WHEN IT WAS CLOSED. HYDROCHLORIC ACID DID NOT START FLOWING FOR APPROXIMATELY 45 SECONDS, EFFECTIVELY LEAVING 24 SECONDS OF PRODUCT FLOW INTO THE CUSTOMER’S STORAGE TANK. ESTIMATION OF 19 GALLONS OF HCL FLOWED IN TO THE STORAGE TANK. THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 250 GALLONS OF BLEACH IN THE CUSTOMER’S STORAGE TANK. WITH THE MIXING OF THE TWO CHEMICALS THERE WAS A RELEASE OF 25 POUNDS OF CHLORINE GAS. THE GAS DISSIPATED SOON AFTER THE VALVE WAS CLOSED.

column162: SVP, TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE AND HEALTH & SAFETY
column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the staging operation, it was discovered that approximately 2 drips of material had escaped from a container. The container was inspected and noted one of the bolts on the container had loosened during transport.  All bolts were inspected and all bolts were tightened down and no further drips were noted. As an additional measure the trailer from which it was offloaded was inspected and no staining was found from the article.  The large switch was then placed in a poly containment pan and strapped down with metal strapping in two different directions to ensure the container would not tip during transit.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of loose bolts or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity.   Generator and Shipper are to ensure container closures are tightened down to specs.  Additionally ensure that all markings are in place and that the container has secondary containment and secured so that tipping of the container in-transit will be avoided.

column168: THE TIDEWATER TRANSIT VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING SOUTHWEST ON TX-61 AND ENTERED A CURVE TO THE LEFT. THE VEHICLE LEFT THE ROADWAY AND OVERTURNED ONTO THE UNPAVED SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY. APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF PRODUCT IN THE BULK TANK WERE RELEASED TO THE GROUND SURFACE THROUGH THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON TOP OF THE TANKER. THE RELEASE WAS A SLOW DRIP FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. THE RELEASE PRODUCT IMPACTED SOIL ON THE SHOULDER, AND WAS ABSORBED BY THE SOIL AND WITH GRANULAR SORBENT MATERIALS. A BERM WAS CONSTRUCTED AROUND THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL MIGRATION OF RELEASED PRODUCT. THE PRODUCT IN THE TANKER WAS OFF-LOADED TO ANOTHER TANKER PROVIDED BY TIDEWATER TRANSIT, AND THE TANK TRAILER AND TRACTOR INVOLVED IN THE COLLISION WERE UP-RIGHTED.     DUE TO THE COLLISION, DAMAGE WAS INCURRED TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TANKER BODY (TANKER UNIT 710); HOWEVER, THE BODY OF THE TANKER WAS NOT PUNCTURED. SURFACE WATER BODIES WERE NOT IMPACTED BY THE PRODUCT RELEASE, AND THE AREA OF IMPACTED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND TRANSPORTED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.     NEITHER INJURIES, FATALITIES, NOR EVACUATIONS WERE ENCOUNTERED DURING THIS INCIDENT.    PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE INCIDENT ARE ATTACHED. A DIAGRAM DEPICTING THE LOCATION OF THE INCIDENT IS ALSO ATTACHED.
column169: A SUMMARY OF THE INCIDENT WAS SHARED WITH COMPANY EMPLOYEES, AND DRIVERS WERE REMINDED TO PRACTICE SAFE DRIVING PRINCIPALS AND PRACTICES.

column25: AMERICAN AVIATION PARTS, INC. DBA GMAIR
column62: Inadequate Procedures; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: NORTHROP GRUMMAN TECHNOLOGY SERVICES RECEIVED 1 EXPLOSIVE CARTRIDGE, APU FIRE BOTTLE THAT WAS RECEIVED WITH THE FOLLOWING DISCREPANCIES:   1.PACKAGE WAS NOT PROPERLY MARKED WITH UN NUMBER, EXPLOSIVE CLASS AND PACKAGING GROUP.  2.APU CARTRIDGE WAS NOT PACKAGED IN ANTI-STATIC BAG (INNER PACKAGING) AS REQUIRED.  3.APU CARTRIDGE DID NOT HAVE THE ANTI-STATIC CAP/PLUG INSTALLED AS REQUIRED.     THE CARTRIDGE PART NUMBER IS AE873571, LOT NUMBER AEN 1-23, WITH A MATERIAL DESCRIPTION OF CARTRIDGE, APU FIRE BOTTLE THAT WAS DROP SHIPPED TO NORTHROP GRUMMAN LAKE CHARLES FROM AMERICAN AVIATION PARTS, INC. DBA GMAIR, VIA STANDARD OVERNIGHT THROUGH FED-EX, WITHOUT DECLARING AND MARKING THE PACKAGE PER CODE OF FEDERAL REGULATIONS SECTION 173, EACH PACKAGE CONTAINING A CLASS 1 MATERIAL MUST BE MARKED WITH THE EX-NUMBER FOR EACH SUBSTANCE, ARTICLE OR DEVICE CONTAINED THEREIN. THE PART WAS THEN CONTAINED IN THE NG STORAGE BUNKER FOR EXPLOSIVES. PROCUREMENT AND SUPPLIER QUALITY NOTIFIED THE SUPPLIER, STATE INDUSTRIAL OF THE NEAR – MISS INCIDENT AND INFORMED THEM NORTHROP GRUMMAN WOULD PROPERLY DISPOSE OF THE CARTRIDGE.    NOTES FROM SECTION 25: AS THIS INCIDENT DID NOT INVOLVE A RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, THERE ARE NO APPLICABLE “HOW FAILED” CODES.
column169: THE SUPPLIER IS BEING ISSUED A SUPPLIER CORRECTIVE ACTION REQUEST FOR THEIR FAILURE TO PROPERLY PACKAGE THE ITEM FOR SHIPMENT; FURTHER BUSINESS WITH THE SUPPLIER HAS BEEN SUSPENDED PENDING ACCEPTABLE RESOLUTION OF THE SUPPLIER CORRECTIVE ACTION REQUEST.    AT A MINIMUM; THE SUPPLIER, AMERICAN AVIATION PARTS, INC. NEEDS TO PUT IN PLACE MORE ABOUT ROBUST TRAINING PROGRAMS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPPING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE THAT SHIPMENTS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARE PROPERLY MARKED, PACKAGED AND PROCESSED FOR SHIPMENT.

column168: On April 4th at approximately 23:38 hrs, a Liquid CO2  Tanker traveling on Lamson Rd (Highway 29, Phoenix, NY) was involved in a single vehicle rollover.  The trailer rolled over, but the tractor remained upright and attached to the unit. The driver lost control of the vehicle which went off the road, struck an electrical pole and rolled over.  Driver was traveling at 55 MPH and the cruise control was not in use.  The driver was wearing his seatbelt and sustained no injuries.  There was no release of hazardous material.
column169: The vessel held up to the rollover with no product release.    Linde has implemented a sleep apnea program and is expanding it to be more of a proactive program as well as investigating a fatigue detection monitoring system.

column168: Event/Claim # 64389..    Our driver was preparing to unload the CTMV..  He took the cap off the unloading hose and product began leaking out..  He shut down the pump and put a bucket underneath the hose..      There was no package failure..  This was human error..  The driver had not tightened the external valve..      The release lasted no more than two (2) minutes..      A bucket was put under the hose and the product was disposed of by the consignee employees..  Some product did get on the gravel and this was cleaned up and disposed of as well by the consignee employees..

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste at the intermediate truck transfer facility was being unloaded for consolidation into a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility. When a forklift operator picked up this individual drum, the top came off, leading to the release. A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and over-packed the drum into a suitable salvage drum along with the absorbent material used to clean up the trailer floor. Any other waste generated in the release was placed in the appropriate facility waste stream for disposal.  The shipment was then loaded without further incident.  Reported to MA DEP at 16:18 on 4/25/17 to Andrew Cooney, RTR# 4-26639. Per MA reporting requirements, this release was also reported to the Braintree, MA fire department at 16:25 on 4/25/17 to Kevin Melligan; he told us that no FD response was required.
column169: Facility personnel including the driver who originally accepted this drum have been given retraining drum closure and package inspection training. We have counselled and mentored facility personnel, including management, as to need for greater oversight and inspection of all loads going in and out of the facility. In addition the facility has been receiving, and will continue to receive, additional inspections of inbound and outbound loads by our compliance department.

column168: Our forklift driver while unloading a trailer, misjudged how short the pallet was and hit the drum behind the pallet he was removing from the trailer. The hole in the drum was about 1"x 2" bottom of 20 gal drum. When the drum was punctured the crew quickly spread floor dry around the drum while at the same time laying the drum on its side to prevent any more liquid from leaking. The response team was called within minutes of the spill. The amount spilled on the ground was about 1/2 gallon and the rest of the drum was put into a containment drum by the response team.
column169: Since the spill, we have re-educated our employees on unloading procedures. All trailers before unloading will have a walk through before entering with a forklift.

column168: Import shipment. Had flown from Basel to Chicago, was damaged during Import storage in Chicago by handling company AGI. Chicago was final destination. Arrival by freighter aircraft.   Forklift blade caused paper bag to tear. Small amount 0.5kg spilled out.   Toxic packing group III, crystal material.   Clean up company HAZCHEM called for emergency response and clean up, staff were cordoned off from the general area. Clean up by Hazchem approx. 20 minutes.   Hazchem cleaned area and took spilled material with for proper disposal. Damaged paper sack placed into revovery drum by Hazchem and was picked up by the consignee along with the rest of the shipment.
column169: The handling company AGI gave corrective action regarding forklift handling of import dangerous goods, in summary :   Use additional skid under base skid of dangerous goods.  When using forklift blade should not be higher than 2-4 inches above ground.  The forklift must be driven backwards   Do not use forklift on ULD (pallets, contains )

column168: Trainyard inspectors in the BNSF Barstow yard smelled an odor directly adjacent to tank car GATX 57099.  Local BNSF Hazmat responders investigated and confirmed odor was coming from GATX 57099 manway due to severely deteriorated manway nozzle gasket.  Car was placarded 1993  and billing confirmed it was a Residue: Last Contained Waste Flammable Liquid N.O.S. STCC 4810560.  Manway gasket was replaced and manway lid properly secured.  No remediation or impact to environment.
column169: Ensure employees loading or unloading tank cars adhere to DOT requirements for pre-trip inspection.  Re-train employees and spot audit as necessary.

column168: On April,  29, 2017, at  18:10 hours, a Transportation Manager at the CSXT North Bergen Yard in North Bergen, NJ reported that UTLX 207098, a loaded tank car of UN1987, Alcohol N.O.S. was leaking from the top of the tank car. The tank car was isolated and the shipper Louis Dreyfus Company,  was notified via Chemtrec, report # 2017-04-29-00120. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the Terminal and found a slow active release from the Bread Box area on top of the tank car. After further inspection the release was found to be from the liquid line valve. It was improperly secured at the base of the valve onto the flange at the pressure plate. The securement nuts on the flange were found less than tool tight and allowing the valve to move from side to side. The flange gasket was inspected and found to be in good condition. The securement nuts were then properly tightened and the valve was properly secured to the flange. The shipper Representative Kevin Sharp with Louis Dreyfus Company (515) 230-8499 was informed of the situation found and the need for OTMA.    To date the tank car is awaiting final FRA One Time Movement Approval to complete the movement to the consignee for offloading and requalification.     NARRI: 5x(5+3+0)x(2+0) = 80  Cause code: 270

column168: Prior to arriving at the location of the incident, the driver loaded 4 drums at customer A’s facility.  During loading the drums were examined in order to make a reasonable determination that the drums had been closed properly.  No defects were noted at the time of loading.  Driver arrived at customer B’s location (site of incident) in order to load additional drums.  Customer A’s drums were required to be segregated from drums being loaded from customer B, and the driver began moving customer A’s drums from their secured position to another location on the vehicle in order to achieve proper segregation.  Driver was using a drum cart with a spring loaded device that held the drum onto the cart, and while moving a drum of customer A’s, the spring failed resulting in the drum falling from the cart.  When the drum struck floor of the vehicle, the bung closure popped out and the drum began to leak the hazardous material contained within.  The bung closure was approximately 2-2.25 inches in diameter.  When the bung closure popped off, the driver sought assistance and proper personal protective equipment in order to safely respond.  From the point of the bung closure popping out to the point the drum was situated to halt the release, roughly 20 gallons of the material was released.  The released material was cleaned up, properly packaged, and transported from the site for disposal.
column169: The terminal operation determined that an additional root cause directly under their control was the defective drum cart used to handle the drum.  The drum cart was disposed of and replaced with new equipment.

column168: On 04/29/2017 this shipment was reported as leaking at the San Bernardino Facility. LARS contacted Hazmat One, which dispatched Ocean Blue to  inspect and remediate leaking condition. column168: A CARGO AGENT OBSERVED THAT ONE OF THE CONTAINERS IN THE SHIPMENT (AIR WAYBILL 173-HNL-12930142) HAD A PIECE OF TAPE WITH "GAS CAPSTAN" WRITTEN ON IT. THE AGENT DECIDED TO REQUEST ADDITIONAL INFORMATION FROM THE DELIVERY DRIVER WHO TENDERED THE SHIPMENT. WHILE THE AGENT WAS TRYING TO LOCATE THE DELIVERY DRIVER, ANOTHER CUSTOMER APPROACHED THE AGENT TO FIND OUT INFORMATION ABOUT THEIR SHIPMENT. THE AGENT DECIDED TO ADDRESS THE CUSTOMER'S CONCERNS WHILE THE SUSPECT SHIPMENT (AIR WAYBILL 173-HNL-12930142) WAS BEING SCREENED. ALTHOUGH NO ALARMS WERE TRIGGERED WHEN THE SUSPECT SHIPMENT WAS SCREENED, THE AGENT DECIDED TO INSPECT THE SHIPMENT FURTHER. ON THE WAY TO INSPECT THE SHIPMENT, ANOTHER CARGO AGENT STATED THAT A CUSTOMER HAD INQUIRED IF THE SHIPMENT (AIR WAYBILL 173-HNL-12930142) HAD PASSED INSPECTION. THE AGENT FOUND THE CUSTOMER'S INQUIRY SUSPICIOUS, AND DECIDED TO OPEN ONE OF THE CRATES. AFTER OPENING THE CRATE, AN ODOR RESEMBLING GASOLINE WAS NOTICED. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, TWO INTERNAL COMBUSTION, FLAMMABLE LIQUID POWERED ENGINES WERE DISCOVERED (UN 3528).THE AGENT TOLD THE CUSTOMER THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS REFUSED BECAUSE IT CONTAINED UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. THE AGENT ALSO NOTIFIED THE CUSTOMER THAT THE SHIPMENT WOULD BE PUT ON HOLD PENDING FAA'S INSPECTION. FAA INSPECTED THE SHIPMENT THE FOLLOWING DAY AND RELEASED THE CARGO.
column169: SUGGESTED RECOMMENDATIONS:IDENTIFY AND USE THOSE SCREENING TECHNOLOGIES (E.G., X-RAY) THAT IMPROVED THE DETECTION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN CARGO; INCREASED ENFORCEMENT BY FAA WOULD ALSO ASSIST IN DETERRING THE SHIPMENT OF UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: ON THURSDAY, 20 APRIL 17' AT APPROXIMATELY 07:15, JCI DRIVER JESUS SALINAS WAS WAITING OUTSIDE OF WEST BASIN CHEVRON TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF 30% CAUSTIC, WHEN HE NOTICED THAT SOME CAUSTIC WAS DRIPPING FROM 'HOSE STORAGE TROUGH' DRAIN OF HIS CAUSTIC TANKER ONTO THE CITY STREET. THE AMOUNT THAT DRIPPED ON TO THE STREET WAS ESTIMATED TO BE LESS THAN A GALLON. FAILURE CAUSE HAD THREE FACTORS. ONE, PREVIOUS DRIVER DID NOT COMPLETELY EMPTY 2" OFF LOADING HOSE PRIOR TO PUTTING 2" HOSE BACK INTO TRAILER HOSE TRAY WITH SMALL AMOUNT OF 30% CAUSTIC STILL IN HOSE.TWO, PREVIOUS DRIVER DID NOT REMOVE HOSE THAT WAS MISSING THE "HOSE CAP".THREE, DRIVER THAT HAD SPILL DID NOT PERFORM A PROPER PRE-TRIP AND IDENTIFY THAT 2" HOSE WAS MISSING HOSE CAP.
column169: ADVISED ALL JCI TORRANCE DRIVERS WITH MEMO REGARDING INSPECTIONS OF ALL HOSES DURING PRE-TRIP AND POST-TRIP INSPECTIONS. THIS SPILL OCCURRENCE AND THE MEMO WERE AN ADDED ITEM FOR THE MONTHLY SAFETY TRAINING SESSION.

CBTX 718470-Petroleum Crude Oil, was found derailed upright with jacket and tank damage as well as fire impingement damage on the B end.  CBTX 718470 did not leak. Contents was transferred into TILX 257984 and transferred billing from CBTX 718470.  Tank cars CBTX 718470 and XCRX 210220 were cleaned and purged and released to mechanical for scrapping.

column168: TRANS-LOAD OPERATOR WAS ON TOP OF THE RAIL-CAR ATTEMPTING TO BEGIN PROCEDURAL OPERATIONS TO VENT THE RAIL-CAR. THE OPERATOR DIDN’T’ VENT THE RAIL-CAR BEFORE PROCEEDING TO REMOVE PRODUCT LINE ON RAIL-CAR. THIS CREATED THE ACID SPILL DUE TO MINOR RAIL-CAR PRESSURE THAT DEVELOPED DURING TRANSIT. THE DURATION OF RELEASE WAS SECONDS. ONCE THE TRANS-LOAD OPERATOR REALIZED HIS ERROR, HE IMMEDIATELY VENTED THE RAIL-CAR BY OPENING THE RAIL-CAR VENT BAIL VALVE. THIS EQUALIZED THE PRESSURE IN THE RAIL-CAR THUS STOPPING THE SULFURIC ACID RELEASE.
column169: OUR CORRECTIVE ACTION IS TWO FOLD. 1) MEETING WITH ALL OPERATION PEOPLE ON LOCATION TO DISCUSS WHAT CAUSED THE RELEASE. 2) WE HAVE CHANGED OUR PROCEDURE TO REFLECT HAVING TWO PEOPLE ON TOP OF A RAIL-CAR BEFORE ANY PART OF THE TOP OF A RAIL-CAR IS TOUCHED. THESE TWO OPERATORS ARE TO CONFIRM PROPER VENTING PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN COMPLETED BEFORE THE PRODUCT LINE CAP IS REMOVED TO HOOK UP ANY TRANSFER HOSES. IF BOTH OPERATORS AGREE THAT THE RAIL-CAR WAS VENTED PROPERLY, THEN THEY CAN CONTINUE TO THE NEXT STEP IN THE PROCESS OF TRANS-LOADING FROM RAIL-CAR TO TRUCK.

column168: NOW OR NEVER TRUCK TRANSPORTING PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON W.C.R 53 AT APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF MILE SOUTH OF W.C.R 46, A HAY TRACTOR ENTERING THE ROADWAY FROM A PRIVATE DRIVEWAY WAS ATTEMPTING TO MAKE A RIGHT HAND TURN TO TRAVEL NORTH ON W.C.R 53. THE HAY TRACTOR EQUIPPED WITH A THREE- PRONG BALE SPIKE ATTACHED DID NOT MAKE A SHARP ENOUGH RIGHT HAND TURN. THIS CAUSED THE FORKS ON THE HAY TRACTOR TO CROSS INTO THE SOUTHBOUND LANE AND STRIKE AND PUNCTURE THE SHELL OF THE TRAILER TRANSPORTING PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL. THE PUNCTURE CAUSED A LOSS OF 16.06 BARRELS WHICH LASTED FOR APPROXIMATELY 20 MINUTES BEFORE THE HOLE WAS PLUGGED AND THE TRAILER WAS OFF-LOADING. BOTH POLICE AND FIRE/EMS WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED WITH NO INJURIES.
column169: DUE TO NO FAULT AND THE RARE NATURE OF THE EVENTS THAT CAUSED THIS INCIDENT, NO ADDITIONAL TRAINING WILL BE REQUIRED.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS SETTING IN HIS TRUCK WHEN HE WAS UNLOADING. I WAS POURING DOWN RAIN. HE RAN A 400 BBL TANK OVER. 7:64 BBLS WAS SPLIT. WE WERE PUTTING BOOMS AND BLOCKING EVERYTHING WE COULD TO KEEP THE OIL FROM GOING ANY FURTHER. column168: WE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL APPROX 10 MINUTES AFTER ACCIDENT OCCURRED. WENT TO SCENE. NORTHRIDE GROUP WAS ON THE SCENE WHEN WE ARRIVED – FUEL WAS SLOWLY LEANING FROM THE FRONT COMPARTMENT – THE TANKER & TRAILER WERE BOTH ON IT’S SIDE – DRIVER WAS UNCONSCIOUS & REMAINED UNCONSCIOUS DURING AMBULANCE DRIVE TO HOSPITAL. A CALL WAS PLACED TO ROY ADAMS FOR CLEANUP – SPILL CONTAINED TO JUST 910 GALLONS FROM ORIGINAL 7800 GALLONS – BOORS WERE PLACED AT ALL AREAS WHERE PRODUCT WAS FLOWING. MOUNTAIN RESEARCHED WORKED WITH DEP TO ENSURE ALL ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES WERE DEALT WITH.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: TRUCK LEFT THE ROADWAY AND ENTERED THE MEDIAN, IT OVERTURNED ON THE DRIVERS SIDE, ROLLING OVER CENTER 5 DEGREES. THE RESULTING CRASH JARRED THE MANHOLE COVERS ON COMPARTMENT ON AND TWO, ENSUING THEM TO LEAK MODERATELY UNTIL THE FIRE RESPONSE TEAM PUT EXTERNAL CLAMPS ON THEM, STOPPING THE LEAKS. THE RESULTING LEAKS LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 200-500 GALLONS OF ETHANOL ONTO THE GROUND.
column169: WE ARE IN THE PROCESS OF GOING OVER OUR PERSONNEL AND MAINTENANCE PROCEDURES. RECHECKING AND RETRAINING WHEREVER IS NEEDED AND OR WARRANTED.

column168: ON 04/08/2017, AT APPROXIMATELY 17:00 HOURS, OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE ABOVE LOCATION WITH A TRUCK & TRAILER LOAD (9000) GALLONS OF AVIATION JET A TO BE DELIVERED AND PUMPED (BY PTO) INTO A 20,000 GALLON ABOVE GROUND TANK.   IN OUR ON THE GROUND INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINE THAT OUR DRIVER HAD UNLOADED THE THREE COMPARTMENTS ON THE TRAILER AND ONE OF THE TWO COMPARTMENTS ON THE TRUCK. HE WAS HOOK UP TO THE LAST COMPARTMENT OF THE TRUCK AND STARTED THE UNLOADING (PUMPING OFF) THE LAST COMPARTMENT WHEN THE HOSE HOOKED TO THE PRESSURE SIDE OF THE PTO AT THE TRUCK C-CLAMP FAILED ARE CAME OFF CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 35 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILL.   OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY DEPLOYED ABSORBENT SPILL PADS AND GREASE SWEEP TO TRY TO PICK UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. HE THEN NOTIFIED THE CUSTOMER AND OUR DISPATCH THAT HE HAD A SPILL.   NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND NRC ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP COMPANY WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.
column169: WE ARE IN THE PROCESS OF INSPECTING ALL TRUCKS TO ASSURE ALL ARE EQUIPPED WITH CAM LOCK TIE DOWN STRAPS OR CLAMPS. WE WILL HAVE SAFETY MEETING AND TRAINING CLASSES STARTING THIRD WEEK OF AUGUST 2017, GOING TO ALL OUR TERMINALS, TO COVER POLICY AND PROCEDURES FOR PUMPING OFF TRUCKS WITH PTO PUMPS.

column168: Approximately 3 lbs. of UN3077 Copper Sulfate released from a 2000 lb. super sack due to an apparent puncture caused by a forklift. The super sack was punctured on the bottom corner. The release impacted a trailer floor. An environmental contractor cleaned the released material and over packed the damaged super sack. All waste was containerized into a poly drum for proper disposal.

During the process of the bobtail truck rollover the piping on the loading/offloading deck on the back of the bobtail cracked at a fitting due to stress on the pipe/fitting during the rollover.   Approximately 65 gallons was released to the atmosphere.  The scene was made safe and a wet rag was placed on the piping to cause it to freeze, stopping the leak temporarily.  The truck was righted using heavy equipment and transported to our Edenton facility where it was pumped off.
column169: There was a camera in this vehicle and it was determined that the incident was caused by the driver becoming distracted.  Significant effort is being made to reduce distracted driving in our company.

column168: TRUCK AND DRIVER WERE TRAVELING EAST BOUND ON THE ATLANTIC CITY EXPRESSWAY, FROM PAULSBORO TO PLESANTVILLE, NJ. THE TRUCK LEFT THE ROADWAY JUST EAST OF THE FARLEY REST AREA. THE TRUCK TRACKED ON THE DIRT AREA OFF THE SHOULDER OF THE LEFT OPERATING LANE. WHEN ATTEMPTING TO BRING THE TRAILER BACK ONTO THE ROAD SURFACE, DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF TRUCK AND JACK KNIFED, RIPPING TRAILER FROM TRACTOR. TANK ROLLED AND LAYING ON ITS TOP, WHEELS UP. FRONT SEAM RUPTURED AND ALL OTHER COMPARTMENTS HAD CRACKS. RESPONSE PERSONNEL WAS DENIED ACCESS TO TRAILER SPILL AREA DUE TO VAPORS. HIGHWAY AUTHORITY WOULD ALLOW NO ONE NEAR THE SPILL, IF ACCESS HAD BEEN GRANTED IN A TIMELY MANNER, THE SPILL COULD HAVE BEEN CONTAINED WITH BOOM.
column169: THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY DRIVER ERROR AS A RESULT OF AN UNDISCLOSED AND PREVIOUSLY UN-DIAGNOSED MEDICAL PROBLEM. IT IS IMPERATIVE THAT CARRIERS BE ALLOWED TO CONTINUE TO TEST FOR SLEEP DISORDERS. DRIVER NEED TO DISCLOSE HEALTH ISSUES THAT WOULD AFFECT PERFORMANCE. CARRIERS NEED TO MONITOR DRIVER PERFORMANCE ON THE ROAD IN ORDER TO TAKE ACTION BEFORE PROBLEMS OCCURS.

column168: THE EVENT OCCURRED ON APRIL 11, 2017 AT 6:30 P.M. REF TRUCKING, INC. WAS FUELING A LARGE FLEET OF LOWELL SCHOOL BUSES ON A PARKING LOT ADJACENT TO THE PAWTUCKET CANAL IN THE ORDINARY COURSE OF BUSINESS. THE FUELER HAD COMPLETED FUELING A NUMBER OF BUSES AND THE FUEL HOSE WAS SEVERAL HUNDRED FEET AWAY FROM THE FUEL TRUCK. AS THE FUELER WAS ROLLING UP THE HOSE HE DETECTED THE SPILL AND REACTED IMMEDIATELY BY SHUTTING OFF THE FUEL AND CALLING HIS SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY, AS INSTRUCTED. A DEFECTIVE COUPLING ON THE HOSE HAD RUPTURED DURING REFUELING, SEPARATING FROM THE HOUSING AND RELEASING DIESEL FUEL TO THE GROUND WHERE IT SPILLED TO THE CANAL. ACCORDING TO REF TRUCKING, INC., THE HOSE WAS NEW, HAVING BEEN REPLACED TWO WEEKS PRIOR TO THE RELEASE. THE CRIMP ON THE HOSE COUPLING CAME OUT OF THE COUPLING DUE TO ITS DEFECT. THE MANUFACTURER, LW TANK WHICH INSTALLED THE HOSE ON MARCH 30, 2017 CAME ON-SITE TO INSPECT THE HOSE ON APRIL 12, 2017 AND ADMITTED VERBALLY THAT THE COUPLING WAS DEFECTIVE. THE DISCHARGE WAS REPORTED TO THE LOWELL FIRE DEPARTMENT WHICH, IN TURN, NOTIFIED TO THE MASSDEP AT 7:25 P.M. ON APRIL 11, 2017.   AS RESULT OF THE DEFECTIVE COUPLING, THE DIESEL FUEL ENTERED THE PAWTUCKET CANAL IN LOWELL TRAVELING ALONG THE ASPHALT PAVEMENT AND DOWN THE CANAL WALL.   BASED UPON CALCULATIONS, REF ESTIMATED A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 700 GALLONS OF ON-ROAD DIESEL FUEL ENTERED THE PAWTUCKET CANAL. TWO (2) BOOMS WERE PRESENT IN THE CANAL AT THE TIME FROM OTHER LANDOWNERS. ONE BOOM WAS 400 FEET UPSTREAM OF THE SPILL AND ON THE OTHER SIDE (NORTH) OF THE CANAL AND HAD LITTLE EFFECT. A SECOND SOFT, ABSORBENT BOOM WAS LOCATED 70 FEET BELOW THE SPILL ON THE NORTH SIDE EXTENDING ON THE OTHER HALF OF THE CANAL. THE BOOM DIRECTED PRODUCT ALONG THE RIGHT SIDE (SOUTH). APPROXIMATELY 680 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RECOVERED FROM THE CANAL. MATERIAL SPILLED: ON-ROAD DIESEL FUEL.   SPILLED DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED FROM THE DEFECTIVE CRIMP TO THE COUPLING ON THE HOSE TO THE ASPHALT PAVEMENT AND FLOWED ACROSS THE PAVED PARKING LOT, ACROSS THE TOP OF THE CANAL WALL, DOWN THE SIDE OF THE GRANITE BLOCK CANAL WALL AND INTO THE CANAL. WATER IN THE CANAL WAS FLOWING IN AN EASTERLY DIRECTION.   DIESEL FUEL WAS RECOVERED AT TWO LOCATIONS DOWNSTREAM TO REDUCE THE POTENTIAL FOR SHEEN, 50 PAYNE STREET AND 556 DUTTON STREET AT THE DUNKIN DONUTS. A PETROLEUM SHEEN WAS NOTED AT A FORK IN THE CANAL, DOWNSTREAM OF THE DUNKIN DONUTS. THIS SHEEN WAS REMEDIED WITH AN ADDITIONAL HARBOR BOOM DEPLOYED DOWNSTREAM. THE LINEAR EXTENT OF THE SHEEN IMPACTS WAS APPROXIMATELY 3,000 FEET. ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE DEPLOYED EFFECTIVELY FURTHER DOWNSTREAM OF THE FORK, NEAR MERRIMACK STREET, AS A PRECAUTION AND TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. (SEE MASSDEP REPORTS. EXHIBIT 5)  NO FISH KILLS, DEAD WATERFOWL OR ANIMALS, STAINED OR DEAD VEGETATION, OR STRAINED SOIL WERE NOTED DURING RESPONSE ACTIONS OR FOLLOW-UP INSPECTIONS.  NO DAMAGE TO PUBLIC OR PRIVATE PROPERTY OCCURRED BECAUSE OF THE NATURE OF THE C

column168: VEHICLE 1 HAD JUST COMPLETED LOADING 2650 GALLONS #2 FUEL ON AT GLOBAL PETROLEUM TERMINAL ON RIVER ROAD, NEWBURGH AND WAS PROCEEDING SOUTH ON ROUTE 9W EN-ROUTE TO US MILITARY ACADEMY. DRIVER ATTEMPTED A RIGHT TURN AT BASE OF LONG BIG VEHICLE. TIPPED OVER ON LEFT SIDE AND SLID ONTO DRUM RIM FRONT BULKHEAD RUPTURED BLOWING APPROXIMATELY 1600 GALLONS OF FUEL ONTO ESCAPE AND FLOW INTO STORM DRAIN AND RUNNING BROOK. FIRST RES-PONDERS APPLIED ABSORBENT PADS, BOOMS, AND ABSORBENT TO LIMIT AND CONTROL FLOW.
column169: CAUSE OF ACCIDENT HAS BEEN DETERMINED TO BE DRIVER ERROR. DRIVER HAD ATTEMPTED A TURN AT SPEED UNSAFE FOR CONDITIONS. MORE EXTENSIVE TRAINING IS REQUIRED TO AVOID A SIMILAR SITUATION IN THE FUTURE.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS ORIGINALLY RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER ON 4/25. THE OUTER BOX HAD AN INDICATION THAT IT CONTAINED AMMUNITION BUT HAD NO OTHER REQUIRED DG MARKINGS, DG LABELING NOR A SHIPPER’S DECLARATION. THEN A PACKAGE THAT LOOKED SIMILAR WAS PICKED UP BUT THIS TIME IT WAS WRAPPED IN WHITE PAPER SO NO MARKINGS WERE VISIBLE. A MANAGER AT THE STATION QUESTIONED THE SHIPMENT. THEY SPOT CHECK OPENED THIS SHIPMENT TO SEE IF THIS PACKAGE CONTAINED AMMUNITION OR NOT AND IT DID CONTAIN AMMUNITION. SINCE THIS OUTER PACKAGE WAS NOT OFFERED BY THE SHIPPER WITH ANY DG MARKINGS, DG LABELING NOR A SHIPPER’S DECLARATION, IT’S BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED OR HIDDEN DG. FAA AGENT PAUL SARAFIN WAS NOTIFIED. FED-EX HELD THE SHIPMENT PENDING FAA INITIAL INSPECTION.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS SPOT CHECKED BY A CALIFORNIA AGRICULTURE INSPECTOR. IT HAD SOME HANDWRITTEN MARKINGS (ARROWS, FRAGILE, TOP) WHICH APPEARED SUSPICIOUS FOR ILLEGAL PLANTS. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS BY MANAGEMENT THEY DID NOT FIND PLANTS BUT DID FIND FIREWORKS. AS THE SHIPPER HAD NOT OFFERED THE SHIPMENT WITH ANY DG MARKINGS, DG LABELS, NOR WITH A SHIPPER’S DECLARATION IT’S BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED OR HIDDEN DG. FAA AGENT WILLIAM CLARK WAS NOTIFIED. I WAS UNABLE TO REACH THE SHIPPER ON THE PHONE NUMBER THEY PROVIDED; MESSAGE SAID VOICE MAIL WAS FULL AND COULD TAKE NO NEW MESSAGES. THE SHIPPER AND RECIPIENT NAME LISTED WAS THE SAME INDIVIDUAL. HOWEVER, WHEN THE RECIPIENT (WHO WAS ALSO LISTED AS THE SHIPPER ON THE AIRBILL) CAME TO THE FEDEX EXPRESS LOCATION TO PICK UP THE SHIPMENT HER LICENSE INDICATED THAT SHE WAS PAMELA FAYE HARRIS, 402 S. BUTTE ST., WILLOWS, CA 95988.

column168: UNIT #1 WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND AT THE 700 BLOCK OF HIGHWAY 181 IN THE FAR LEFT NB LANE AND FAILED TO MAINTAIN HIS SINGLE LANE OF TRAVEL WHILE ENTERING A CURVE WHICH RESULTED IN UNIT #1 VEERING INTO THE FAR RIGHT NB LANE OF TRAVEL. AS A RESULT OF THE ACTIONS OF UNIT #1 THE UNIT #3 VEHICLE ATTEMPTED TO AVOID BEING STRUCK HOWEVER CONTACT WAS STILL MADE BY UNIT # 2 TRAILER TO THE LEFT SIDE OF UNIT #4 WHICH THEN PUSHED THE UNIT #4 TRAILER INTO A TX DOT CONCRETE BARRIER. THE UNIT #3 VEHICLE WAS UNABLE TO CONTROL HIS LOAD WHICH SHIFTED AS A RESULT OF THE CRASH IMPACT AND IT OVERTURNED IMMEDIATELY CATCHING FIRE WITH CRUDE OIL ON BOARD. THE UNIT #2 TRAILER ALSO OVERTURNED AND PARTIALLY RESTED ON THE SIDE OF THE UNIT #4 TRAILER. UPON THE DRIVERS WERE ABLE TO EXIT THEIR CABS AND RUN FROM THE SCENE TO AVOID BEING BURNED. A VIDEO SURVEILLANCE FOOTAGE FROM THE ACCIDENT SCENE WAS ABLE TO CAPTURE THE ACCIDENT AND IT WAS THE EVENTS LISTED ABOVE. DIGITAL PHOTOGRAPHS WERE TAKEN AT THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT AND DOWNLOADED TO CCPD CASE REPORT #1704060045    ESTIMATED SPEED OF OUR TRUCK 30 MPH. ESTIMATED SPEED OF TRUCK CAUSING ACCIDENT 40-4 MPH. WEATHER WAS SUNNY AND HOT, 85 DEGREES
